# TMDB Live Search Mode (Web UI)

## Purpose

Add a user-invoked TMDB search path that is separate from the default multi-source search flow.

When the user clicks `Search TMDB`:

- results are fetched live from TMDB
- the results view shows only TMDB sections
- rows remain clickable for the existing details modal flow
- each TMDB media row exposes a manual `ADD TO REDIS` action

## Endpoints

### `GET /api/search/tmdb`

- Query params:
  - `q` (required, min length 2)
  - `limit` (default 10, max 50)
- Returns:
  - `tmdb_mode: true`
  - `tmdb_movie: []`
  - `tmdb_tv: []`
  - `exact_match: null`
- Result rows are normalized into Redis-document-like shape for consistent rendering (`mc_id`, `source_id`, `mc_type`, `search_title`, `image`, `overview`, etc.).
- Rows include `_tmdb_live: true` so UI can render TMDB-specific actions.

### `POST /api/tmdb/add-to-redis`

- Query params:
  - `tmdb_id` (required, numeric)
  - `mc_type` (`movie` or `tv`)
- Behavior:
  - fetch full TMDB details via `TMDBService.get_media_details`
  - normalize through `normalize_document`
  - serialize through `document_to_redis`
  - write to `media:{mc_id}` in Redis
  - attempt Media Manager propagation by calling `MediaManagerClient.insert_docs([doc])` after Redis write
  - apply `passes_media_manager_filter` before enqueueing to Media Manager
  - preserve existing `created_at` when updating an existing document
- Response includes:
  - `status` (`inserted` or `updated`)
  - `id` (Redis key)
  - `media_manager` object with enqueue/skip/error details
  - full inserted/updated document

## UI Behavior

- Button: `Search TMDB` on the search row in `home.html`.
- TMDB mode categories:
  - `TMDB Movies`
  - `TMDB TV`
- Standard category rendering is skipped while `tmdb_mode === true`.
- For `_tmdb_live` media rows, render `ADD TO REDIS`.
- `ADD TO REDIS` is manual-only; TMDB searches do not auto-insert into Redis.
